<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<pageBreakToken pageId="3" pageNumber="4" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jost, Oleas &amp; Meerow" authorityYear="2015" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis ruthiana" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="ruthiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Eucharis ruthiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meerow" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Baker" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis moorei" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="moorei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Eucharis moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Baker) Meerow (
<bibRefCitation author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Sida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="29 - 49" refId="B3" refString="Meerow, AW, 1987a. New species of Phaedranassa and Eucharis (Amaryllidaceae). Sida 12: 29 - 49" title="New species of Phaedranassa and Eucharis (Amaryllidaceae)." volume="12" year="1987 a">Meerow 1987a</bibRefCitation>
), placing it in 
<taxonomicName class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis (Heterocharis) subsp. subg." order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="subGenus" species="moorei" subGenus="Heterocharis" subSpecies="subg.">Eucharis subg. Heterocharis</taxonomicName>
Meerow, characterized by large campanulate, fragrant flowers, numerous ovules per locule, and green mature capsules (
<bibRefCitation author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="136 - 220" publicationUrl="10.2307/2399347" refId="B5" refString="Meerow, AW, 1989. Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 136 - 220, DOI: 10.2307/2399347" title="Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/2399347" volume="76" year="1989">Meerow 1989</bibRefCitation>
). It differs from this species by the narrower leaves and tepals, mild (vs. strong) fragrance, deeply cleft staminal corona with long marginal teeth, the incurved free filaments, and the short style (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Contrasting features of Eucharis ruthiana and Eucharis moorei." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" tableUuid="E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572">2</tableCitation>
). From the putative hybrid 
<taxonomicName class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis grandiflora" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="grandiflora">
Eucharis 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ã—">x</normalizedToken>
grandiflora
</taxonomicName>
Planch. &amp; Lind., (1853) it differs by the long staminal teeth and its fertility.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Table-UUID="E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" start="Table 2" startId="T2">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Table 2.</emphasis>
