<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution and ecology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jost, Oleas &amp; Meerow" authorityYear="2015" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis ruthiana" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="ruthiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis ruthiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from the type locality and a private reserve in southern Ecuador (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Eucharis ruthiana. A Plant in cultivation B-C Leaves B Adaxial view C Abaxial view D-H Flowers D Upper portion of inflorescence showing flower habit E Flower cut and spread to show staminal corona F Dorsal-ventral view of limb showing the spread of the androecium G Lateral view H Lateral view with three tepals removed to show androecium I Ovary dissected to show numerous, superposed, globose ovules J Distribution of Eucharis ruthiana in Ecuador (black stars). Map courtesy of www. freeworldmaps. net." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.48.4399.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/41393" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">3I</figureCitation>
), in lower montane rain forest where it grows on stony soil in the understory of dense forest at ca. 1100 m elevation. A large population occurs on the Copalinga private reserve near Zamora according to the property owner.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">The species is named in honor of the late Ruth Moore, ardent supporter of conservation efforts in Ecuador.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis (Heterocharis) subsp. subg." order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="subGenus" species="ruthiana" subGenus="Heterocharis" subSpecies="subg.">Eucharis subg. Heterocharis</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="136 - 220" publicationUrl="10.2307/2399347" refId="B5" refString="Meerow, AW, 1989. Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 136 - 220, DOI: 10.2307/2399347" title="Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/2399347" volume="76" year="1989">Meerow (1989)</bibRefCitation>
, even though it appeared paraphyletic in his cladistic analysis of morphological characters. The large, fragrant flowers; numerous ovules per locule, and mature green fruits were considered symplesiomorphic for the genus. The subgenus previously included only two fertile species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baker" authorityYear="1883" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis sanderi" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="sanderi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis sanderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Baker, JG" journalOrPublisher="Curtis's Botanical Magazine" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="B1" refString="Baker, JG, 1883. Eucharis sanderi. Curtis's Botanical Magazine 109" title="Eucharis sanderi." volume="109" year="1883">Baker (1883)</bibRefCitation>
, endemic to the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="ChocÃ³">Choco</normalizedToken>
region of Colombia, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meerow" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Baker" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis moorei" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="moorei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Baker) 
<bibRefCitation author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Sida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="29 - 49" refId="B3" refString="Meerow, AW, 1987a. New species of Phaedranassa and Eucharis (Amaryllidaceae). Sida 12: 29 - 49" title="New species of Phaedranassa and Eucharis (Amaryllidaceae)." volume="12" year="1987 a">Meerow (1987a)</bibRefCitation>
, found on both the eastern and western declivities of the Ecuadorean Andes. The group also contains two apparently sterile taxa, 
<taxonomicName class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis grandiflora" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="grandiflora">
Eucharis 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ã—">x</normalizedToken>
grandiflora
</taxonomicName>
Planch. &amp; Lind. (1853), a putative hybrid of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meerow" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Baker" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis moorei" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="moorei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baker" authorityYear="1883" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis sanderi" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="sanderi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis sanderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, found in southern Colombia and northern Ecuador (
<bibRefCitation author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="136 - 220" publicationUrl="10.2307/2399347" refId="B5" refString="Meerow, AW, 1989. Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 136 - 220, DOI: 10.2307/2399347" title="Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/2399347" volume="76" year="1989">Meerow 1989</bibRefCitation>
), most often in cultivation, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linden ex Planch" authorityYear="1857" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis amazonica" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lind. ex Planch. (
<bibRefCitation author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="416 - 422" publicationUrl="10.2307/1220981" refId="B8" refString="Meerow, AW, Dehgan, B, 1984. Re-establishment and lectotypification of Eucharis amazonica Linden ex Planchon (Amaryllidaceae). Taxon 33: 416 - 422, DOI: 10.2307/1220981" title="Re-establishment and lectotypification of Eucharis amazonica Linden ex Planchon (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/1220981" volume="33" year="1984">Meerow and Dehgan 1984</bibRefCitation>
). The latter, most commonly found in the lower Huallaga Valley of Peru, never sets seed, has a triploid-derived chromosome number (2 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">n</emphasis>
= 68), and impaired pollen fertility (
<bibRefCitation author="Nagalla, L" journalOrPublisher="Microbioscience Letters" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="89 - 94" refId="B11" refString="Nagalla, L, 1979. Cytological studies in Eucharis grandiflora Planch. and Linden. Microbioscience Letters 4: 89 - 94" title="Cytological studies in Eucharis grandiflora Planch. and Linden." volume="4" year="1979">Nagalla 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1559 - 1575" publicationUrl="10.2307/2444050" refId="B4" refString="Meerow, AW, 1987b. Chromosome cytology of Eucharis, Caliphruria, and Urceolina (Amaryllidaceae). American Journal of Botany 74: 1559 - 1575, DOI: 10.2307/2444050" title="Chromosome cytology of Eucharis, Caliphruria, and Urceolina (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/2444050" volume="74" year="1987 b">Meerow 1987b</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jost, Oleas &amp; Meerow" authorityYear="2015" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis ruthiana" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="ruthiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis ruthiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meerow" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Baker" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis moorei" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="moorei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is easily separable (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Contrasting features of Eucharis ruthiana and Eucharis moorei." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" tableUuid="E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572">2</tableCitation>
) by the narrower leaves and tepals, the deeply cleft staminal cup with long marginal teeth, the short, nearly filiform, incurved free filaments, and the relatively short style.
